        <p> ___Twig_token_1___ finally some Canadian culture and tradition. Like so much in Canada, this has to do with food. Because the North Americans are on nutrition. I am only surprised that people here are not thicker than in Germany. </p>
        <p> One of the typical yellow school buses drives us out of Montreal for an hour and into the forest. There is still a lot of snow here. We are reloaded to a horse -drawn trail and find ourselves at a few wooden huts. Ahorn syrup is manufactured here. Small metal buckets hang everywhere on the tree trunks. An inspection shows that the raw tree juice of the sugar maple runs into it. The syrup will later become of this. </p>
        <p> In one of the wooden huts is a large hall that is a little reminiscent of a Bavarian beer tent with a fireplace. So simple benches and tables and good mood. But instead of brass music, there is violin and guitar. I prefer it too. </p>
        <p> The Canadians take this Sugar Shag very seriously. So it is not a tourist event. A waitress briefly explains what to eat, and then it starts. Large bowls with soup, meat, mashed potatoes and more meat are passed around. There are still pancakes for dessert. </p>

